---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Core concepts — Aitroop Docs',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="concepts">
    <h1>Core concepts</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      The whole platform comes down to two modes and three primitives. Once you have this mental model,
      everything else in the docs is just elaboration.
    </p>

    <h2>The two modes</h2>
    <p>
      Aitroop has exactly two surfaces for working with the agent. The distinction matters because they
      serve different jobs.
    </p>

    <h3>Chat — for exploration</h3>
    <p>
      An open-ended conversation with the agent. You don't know yet exactly what you want, or you do but
      you haven't figured out the right phrasing. Try things. Throw away results. Try again. Chat is cheap
      and disposable on purpose.
    </p>

    <h3>App — for repetition</h3>
    <p>
      A frozen, parameterized version of a working chat. The exploration is done; this is the version that
      runs the same way every time. You give it a form, optional schedules, and access controls. Your whole
      team uses it without rewriting the prompt.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>The shortest possible summary.</strong> Chat is for finding what works. App is for running it on repeat.
      Every App in your library started life as a chat.
    </div>

    <h2>The formula</h2>
    <p>An App, broken down to its parts:</p>
    <div class="code-block" style="text-align:center;font-size:0.9375rem;padding:1.25rem;">
      <strong style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">App</strong> = <strong style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">AppInput</strong>[] + <strong style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">Stage</strong>[] + <strong style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">Artifact</strong>[]
    </div>
    <p>
      Three primitives. Most Apps use one of each. Some use several of each. The mental model holds either way.
    </p>

    <h2>AppInput — the form</h2>
    <p>
      A schema-driven form field. The shape of an AppInput tells the platform how to render it and how to
      validate it. The set of AppInputs is what makes an App reusable: same workflow, different inputs.
    </p>
    <p>Built-in AppInput types:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>text</code> — single-line or multi-line free-form text.</li>
      <li><code>daterange</code> — start date and end date with a picker.</li>
      <li><code>select</code> — single or multi-select from a list of options.</li>
      <li><code>file</code> — direct file upload from the user's machine.</li>
      <li><code>connect_file</code> — pick a file from one of your authorized Connects (a Drive document, a Notion page, etc.).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      When you click <strong>Save as App</strong> on a chat, the agent proposes a starting set of AppInputs
      based on what varied in your conversation. You can add, remove, or reorder them before saving.
    </p>

    <h2>Stage — the agent session</h2>
    <p>
      A Stage is one self-contained agent session with one goal. The Stage owns the prompt, the agent's
      reasoning, the tools it can call (Skills and Connects), and the format of the final output.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most Apps need exactly one Stage. The agent reads the AppInputs, does the work, produces the
      Artifact, and you're done.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Multi-stage Apps</strong> exist for workflows where the natural output of one job is the input
      of the next. Stage 1 produces a list of companies; Stage 2 enriches each one; Stage 3 writes the
      outreach drafts. Each stage gets the previous stage's artifacts as its starting context. The platform
      handles the wiring.
    </p>

    <h2>Artifact — the deliverable</h2>
    <p>
      The output you actually care about. Artifacts are first-class: they have a type, they can be
      previewed in the UI, they can be edited, they can be downloaded, and they can be fed into the next
      Stage of a multi-stage App.
    </p>
    <p>Built-in Artifact types:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>markdown</code> — reports, summaries, documents.</li>
      <li><code>code</code> — scripts and source files, syntax-highlighted.</li>
      <li><code>html</code> — rendered web pages, dashboards, slide decks.</li>
      <li><code>json</code> — structured data with schema preview.</li>
      <li><code>csv</code> — tabular data; rendered as a table.</li>
      <li><code>image</code> — diagrams, charts, generated images.</li>
      <li><code>file</code> — anything else (PDF, ZIP, binary).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      See <a href="/docs/artifacts">Artifact formats</a> for the full reference on each type.
    </p>

    <h2>The supporting pieces</h2>
    <p>
      The two modes and three primitives are the model. Three more pieces make the model useful in practice:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/skills">Skills</a></strong> — reusable capability modules the agent can call.
        Things like <code>web-scrape</code>, <code>lead-finder</code>, <code>seo-audit</code>, <code>github-mcp</code>.
        Install once; available in every chat and every App from then on.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/connects">Connects</a></strong> — OAuth integrations into the systems you already
        use. Gmail, Drive, GitHub, Salesforce, HubSpot, Notion. The agent reads and writes through your authorized account.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/schedules">Schedules</a></strong> — cron expressions that run any App
        automatically. Daily reports, hourly polling, weekly digests. Results delivered to wherever you want them.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The whole loop</h2>
    <p>
      Putting it all together: you authorize the <em>Connects</em> you need. You install the <em>Skills</em> that
      match your work. You open a <em>Chat</em>, ask the agent to do a real task, and iterate until the
      <em>Artifact</em> looks right. You click Save; the platform turns the conversation into an <em>App</em>
      with <em>AppInputs</em> and one or more <em>Stages</em>. You add a <em>Schedule</em>. Now the work runs itself.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Next</span>
      <a href="/docs/chat">Chat mode in depth</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
